<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=0 WIDTH="95%"><TR ><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#F0DCA0" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Lord_Konradt</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I was wondering what everybodies opinion is about party in Project C or not.<P>Personally I like it when there is no party, This way you have more bonding with your alter-ego. And it makes Realtime gameplay more pleasant, and less complex. The other advantage is that in multiplayer, you could have your own character to relate to. And maybe make it possible to keep your character in both multiplayer, and single-player. I know this could make the game imbalanced, because you can start a game with a super hero, but this could be fixed, by making the difficulty of the game, biased towards the level of the character. (just a thought that pop'ed in my head).<BR>Not having a personnal character was actually one of the things I did not like in Baldur's Gate ( and other RPG's), was that you could  not really do this. You could make a blue print of your character, but that felt so fake. But the worst thing was the joint inventory. That was sooo bad. Our first(and our last) multiplayer was completely ruined by this. Because of the joint inventory, One person could spend all the money, without consent. I know that there was an alternative, but this I found was even worse. I could imagine the quarrels one could have of who, would be this leader.<P>So What I mean is ...<BR>I like it the most when there is only a party in multiplayer (it would be difficult if there wasn't :-) ). And that you have nearly complete control over that character, and his belongings.<P>I hope you understood anything about this ranting :-).<BR><P>------------------<BR>Greetz,<BR>Lord Konradt.<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hehe  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"> I think there are some people who'll disagree, but I for one agree  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"> Otoh, there are some very good points in favor of a party, and probably it's possible to blend both advantages without too much disadvantages. <P><BR>Lar</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Renyx</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I believe almost everybody on this forum will disagree...except for me and Konradt that is  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>&gt;&gt;probably it's possible to blend both advantages without too much disadvantages.<P>I hope that doesn't mean it will be necessary to switch to turn based combat, because I think that will ruin the gameplay ... for me anyway.<P>Two questions for Lar :<BR>Will there be cinematics in Project C ?<BR>Is that super secret multiplayer option (yes, that one) included in Project C ? <P>Renyx</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Arhu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hehe! You've <I>waited</I> for this topic, haven't you, Lar?  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P>Anyway, with a single character there is always the risk that the game will become another stupid hack and slay "RPG". Well, I played Diablo a lot, but that game didn't have <I>any</I> puzzles, story...  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/frown.gif"><BR>And normally you don't go on adventures alone, but with a party, cause it's more fun.<BR>But I think in a CRPG it's better to let the other characters be played by other people or by the computer. It <I>is</I> imho easier to identify with a single character than with an entire party. I would appreciate NPC's joining you on your journey, though.<BR>And to multiplayer mode: This is the best way to form a party, I think. Game balancing is difficult, I presume, but then there would be a <I>real</I> party.<P>Renyx, I don't think that super secret multiplayer option will be implemented in Project C...<BR>... right  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/icons/icon5.gif"><P><I>Meow...</I><BR>Arhu</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Bronthion</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I prefer playing a party, because:<P>1) more tactical fighting possible (no stupid hack'n'slay)<BR>2) no realtime combat possible, at least none without pause function (if I want realtime combat, I play Duke Nukem, but no RPG)<BR>3) relationships between characters<BR>4) if I play only one character, he/she must be able to do anything (super hero), but if I play a group, I can have one thief, one mage, one warrior, one cleric, etc. I think these characters are more realistic than a lonesome cowboy.<P>IMO it is more important for a good identification with the character(s), that "I" can define him/her/them, and not playing a pre-defined character. I want to give him/her/them an individual character portrait, voice, name and history. I can live without that, but I think this is the best way of forming a relationship with him/her/them (because then, he/she is MY creation, and not from sombody else).<P>------------------<BR>Bronthion, der dunkle Halb-Elf<BR>Bronthion, the dark Half-Elf<P><p>[This message has been edited by Bronthion (edited 26-12-1999).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Risini Visinimi</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hi All!<P>I don't like to run arround alone, but I even like it to have only one Char. to identify 